/*
https://leetcode.com/problems/house-robber/description/?envType=company&envId=nvidia&favoriteSlug=nvidia-three-months

You are a professional robber planning to rob houses along a street. Each house has a certain amount of money stashed, the only constraint stopping you from robbing each of them is that adjacent houses have security systems connected and it will automatically contact the police if two adjacent houses were broken into on the same night.

Given an integer array nums representing the amount of money of each house, return the maximum amount of money you can rob tonight without alerting the police.

 

Example 1:

Input: nums = [1,2,3,1]
Output: 4
Explanation: Rob house 1 (money = 1) and then rob house 3 (money = 3).
Total amount you can rob = 1 + 3 = 4.
Example 2:

Input: nums = [2,7,9,3,1]
Output: 12
Explanation: Rob house 1 (money = 2), rob house 3 (money = 9) and rob house 5 (money = 1).
Total amount you can rob = 2 + 9 + 1 = 12.
 

Constraints:

1 <= nums.length <= 100
0 <= nums[i] <= 400

*/

  /*
This is a classic Dynamic Programming problem.
At every house, you have only 2 choices:
Rob current house
Then you cannot rob the previous house.
Money = nums[i] + best until i-2
Skip current house
Then best money remains same as previous house.
Money = best until i-1

I define dp[i] as the maximum money we can rob from index 0 to i. 
At every house, I either rob it or skip it. If I rob it, I add nums[i] to dp[i-2].
If I skip it, the answer is dp[i-1]. So dp[i] = max(nums[i] + dp[i-2], dp[i-1]).
    */

class Solution {
  
    public int rob(int[] nums) {
        int n = nums.length;

        // If there is only one house, rob that house
        if (n == 1) {
            return nums[0];
        }

        /*
         dp[i] means:
         maximum money we can rob from house 0 to house i
         without robbing two adjacent houses.
        */
        int[] dp = new int[n];

        // For the first house, only one option: rob house 0
        dp[0] = nums[0];

        /*
         For first two houses, we cannot rob both.
         So choose the house with more money.
        */
        dp[1] = Math.max(nums[0], nums[1]);

        /*
         For each house i, we have two choices:

         Choice 1: Rob current house
                   Then we cannot rob house i-1.
                   Total = nums[i] + dp[i - 2]

         Choice 2: Skip current house
                   Then best remains dp[i - 1]

         Take the maximum of both choices.
        */
        for (int i = 2; i < n; i++) {
            dp[i] = Math.max(nums[i] + dp[i - 2], dp[i - 1]);
        }

        // Final answer is best amount from house 0 to last house
        return dp[n - 1];
    }
}
